              <h2><span style="font-weight: bold;">IP Addressing</span></h2>
              The internet runs on IP addressing and routing.  Today we use two
              versions of IP addressing on the internet, Internet Protocol
              version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6). Both IPv4
              and IPv6 addresses have finite pools of numbers.<br />
              <br />
              For IPv4 the address is 32-bits in size and contains a total of
              4,294,967,296 addresses. An IPv6 address is 128-bits and contains
              340,282,366,920,938,463,463,374,607,431,768,211,456 address.
              Origanly the IPv4 32 bit address space was thought to be much
              bigger then was needed.  In the 90s everyone started using the
              internet and the IPv4 address space was running out, so IPv6 was
              proposed. <br />
              <br />
              Not every IP address in the IPv4 or IPv6 pools can be assigned to
              internet devices.  Some address are reserved and will not route. 
              These address can only be used on internal networks.<br />
              <ul>
                <li>10.0.0.0/8 IP addresses: 10.0.0.0 -- 10.255.255.255</li>
                <li>172.16.0.0/12 IP addresses: 172.16.0.0 -- 172.31.255.255</li>
                <li>192.168.0.0/16 IP addresses: 192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255</li>
                <li>127.0.0.1 is reserved for loopback addressing</li>
                <li>The IPv6 private network pool is fc00::/7 </li>
              </ul>
              <h3>IPv4 Subnets</h3>
              <p>Subnets are used to divided the address space into blocks for
                routing.  The networks are categorized into 5  groups or Class
                A, B, C, D &amp; E. Class A networks have their address range
                from 1-126, Class B from 128-191, Class C from 192-223, Class D
                from 224-239, Class E from 240-255. </p>
              <p>A Mask is used to further divide the IP range.  When read in
                binary, a subnet Mask will always be a string of 1's followed by
                a string of 0's. The 1's cover the static part of the address
                while the 0's cover addressable space in the subnet.  So if we
                split a class A network into 255 class B networks the mask would
                be 255.255.0.0 or 11111111.11111111 00000000.00000000 in binary
                where the first 2 octets are used to address the network, so the
                class A now works like a class B.</p>
              <p>The following table shows the mask, bits and number of host.</p>
