              <br />
              <h3>IPv6 Subneting </h3>
              <p class="MsoNormal">An IPv6 subnet mask is basically the same as
                an IPv4 subnet but has more digets like the IPv6 address. IPv6
                uses a 128 bits for each IP address, as opposed to IPv4's 32 bit
                address, and those 128 bits are divided into 16-bit words (not 8
                bit like IPv4), so an IPv6 address looks like this in binary.<br />
                <br />
0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000.0000000000000000</p>
              <p class="MsoNormal">The subnetting is the same where we divide
                the address into ones and zeros.  As IPv6 has so many more
                possibilities a table is not shown.</p>
